<question type="stack">
  <name>
    <text>Week 10 – Q5: Parallel RLC Natural Response (Two-Switch Circuit)</text>
  </name>
  <questiontext format="html">
    <text><![CDATA[
<h3>Week 10 &ndash; Q5: Parallel RLC Natural Response (Two-Switch Circuit)</h3>
<p><em>Course: Electromagnetism and Circuit Analysis &mdash; LUT University, Finland</em></p>
<p><em>This is a training exercise &mdash; you may use books, tutors, and AI. The question requires multi-step reasoning.</em></p>
<p><strong>Total: 8 points | Penalty per wrong attempt: 10%</strong></p>

<hr />

<p>The two switches in the circuit shown below operate synchronously.
When switch&nbsp;1 is in position&nbsp;<strong>a</strong>, switch&nbsp;2 is in position&nbsp;<strong>d</strong>.
When switch&nbsp;1 moves to position&nbsp;<strong>b</strong>, switch&nbsp;2 moves to position&nbsp;<strong>c</strong>.
Switch&nbsp;1 has been in position&nbsp;<strong>a</strong> for a long time.</p>

<p>At \(t = 0\), the switches move to their alternate positions. Find \(v_o(t)\) for \(t \geq 0\).</p>

<p><strong>Circuit parameters:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Current source: \(I_s = {@Is_val@}\;\text{A}\)</li>
  <li>Left-side resistor: \(R_a = {@Ra_val@}\;\Omega\)</li>
  <li>Inductor: \(L = {@L_mH@}\;\text{mH}\)</li>
  <li>Parallel resistor: \(R = {@R_val@}\;\Omega\)</li>
  <li>Right-side resistor: \(R_b = {@Rb_val@}\;\Omega\)</li>
  <li>DC voltage source: \(V_{dc} = {@Vdc_val@}\;\text{V}\)</li>
  <li>Capacitor: \(C = {@C_uF@}\;\mu\text{F}\)</li>
</ul>

<p><img src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/q5_parallel_rlc_natural_switches.svg" alt="Two-switch parallel RLC circuit" style="max-width:550px;" /></p>

<hr />

<h4>Part (a) &mdash; Initial Capacitor Voltage \(V_0\) (1 pt)</h4>
<p>Before the switches flip (\(t &lt; 0\)), the circuit has been in DC steady state for a long time.
At DC steady state, the capacitor is an <strong>open circuit</strong> (no current flows through it or \(R_b\)).
What is the initial capacitor voltage \(V_0 = v_o(0^-)\) in Volts?</p>
<p>\(V_0 = \) [[input:ans1]] V [[validation:ans1]]</p>
<p><em>Syntax hint: Enter a number, e.g. <code>100</code></em></p>

<hr />

<h4>Part (b) &mdash; Initial Inductor Current \(I_0\) (1 pt)</h4>
<p>At DC steady state (\(t &lt; 0\)), the inductor is a <strong>short circuit</strong>.
What is the initial inductor current \(I_0 = i_L(0^-)\) in Amperes?</p>
<p>\(I_0 = \) [[input:ans2]] A [[validation:ans2]]</p>
<p><em>Syntax hint: Enter a number, e.g. <code>5</code></em></p>

<hr />

<h4>Part (c) &mdash; Damping Coefficient \(\alpha\) (1 pt)</h4>
<p>After the switches flip (\(t &gt; 0\)), the sources are disconnected and the circuit
becomes a source-free <strong>parallel</strong> RLC circuit with \(R = {@R_val@}\;\Omega\),
\(L = {@L_mH@}\;\text{mH}\), and \(C = {@C_uF@}\;\mu\text{F}\).</p>
<p>Calculate the damping coefficient \(\alpha = \frac{1}{2RC}\) in rad/s.</p>
<p>\(\alpha = \) [[input:ans3]] rad/s [[validation:ans3]]</p>
<p><em>Syntax hint: Enter a number, e.g. <code>400</code></em></p>

<hr />

<h4>Part (d) &mdash; Resonant Frequency \(\omega_0\) (1 pt)</h4>
<p>Calculate the undamped resonant frequency \(\omega_0 = \frac{1}{\sqrt{LC}}\) in rad/s.</p>
<p>\(\omega_0 = \) [[input:ans4]] rad/s [[validation:ans4]]</p>
<p><em>Syntax hint: Enter a number, e.g. <code>500</code></em></p>

<hr />

<h4>Part (e) &mdash; Damping Regime Classification (1 pt)</h4>
<p>Compare \(\alpha^2\) with \(\omega_0^2\) and classify the damping regime:</p>
<p>Select your answer: [[input:ans5]] [[validation:ans5]]</p>

<hr />

<h4>Part (f) &mdash; General Response Form (1 pt)</h4>
<p>Write the <strong>general form</strong> of \(v_o(t)\) for \(t \geq 0\),
appropriate to the damping regime you identified. Use symbolic constants
(<code>A1, A2</code> for overdamped; <code>B1, B2</code> for underdamped;
<code>D1, D2</code> for critically damped).</p>
<p><strong>Note:</strong> This is a <strong>natural response</strong> (source-free circuit), so there is no forced (steady-state) term.</p>
<p>\(v_o(t) = \) [[input:ans6]] [[validation:ans6]]</p>
<p><em>Syntax hint: Use <code>exp(...)</code>, <code>sin(...)</code>, <code>cos(...)</code>,
and <code>t</code>. Example: <code>A1*exp(-20.9*t) + A2*exp(-479.1*t)</code></em></p>

<hr />

<h4>Part (g) &mdash; Complete \(v_o(t)\) with Numerical Coefficients (1 pt)</h4>
<p>Apply the initial conditions
\(v_o(0^+) = V_0 = {@V0_val@}\;\text{V}\) and
\(\frac{dv_o}{dt}(0^+) = -\frac{1}{C}\!\left(\frac{V_0}{R} + I_0\right) = {@dvdt0@}\;\text{V/s}\)
to find all coefficients numerically.</p>
<p>Enter the complete expression for \(v_o(t)\) with all numerical values substituted.</p>
<p>\(v_o(t) = \) [[input:ans7]] V [[validation:ans7]]</p>
<p><em>Syntax hint: Use <code>exp(...)</code>, <code>sin(...)</code>, <code>cos(...)</code>,
and <code>t</code>. Example: <code>100*exp(-400*t)*cos(300*t) - 800*exp(-400*t)*sin(300*t)</code></em></p>

<hr />

<h4>Part (h) &mdash; Final Value Verification (1 pt)</h4>
<p>What is \(\lim_{t \to \infty} v_o(t)\)?</p>
<p>Read off the steady-state value directly from your \(v_o(t)\) expression &mdash;
the constant term that remains as all exponentials decay to zero.</p>
<p>\(\lim_{t \to \infty} v_o(t) = \) [[input:ans8]] V [[validation:ans8]]</p>
<p><em>Syntax hint: Enter a number, e.g. <code>0</code></em></p>
]]></text>
  </questiontext>

  <generalfeedback format="html">
    <text><![CDATA[
<h3>Worked Solution</h3>

<h4>Step 1: Initial Conditions (DC Steady State for \(t < 0\))</h4>
<p>With switch&nbsp;1 at position&nbsp;a and switch&nbsp;2 at position&nbsp;d for a long time:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Capacitor voltage:</strong> At DC steady state, the capacitor is an open circuit.
      No current flows through \(R_b\), so \(V_0 = V_{dc} = {@V0_val@}\;\text{V}\).</li>
  <li><strong>Inductor current:</strong> At DC steady state, the inductor is a short circuit.
      All of \(I_s\) flows through the inductor: \(I_0 = I_s = {@I0_val@}\;\text{A}\).</li>
</ul>

<h4>Step 2: Circuit for \(t > 0\)</h4>
<p>After the switches flip, the sources are disconnected. The remaining circuit is a
source-free parallel RLC: \(R = {@R_val@}\;\Omega\), \(L = {@L_val@}\;\text{H}\),
\(C = {@C_val@}\;\text{F}\).</p>

<h4>Step 3: Damping Parameters</h4>
<p>\[\alpha = \frac{1}{2RC} = \frac{1}{2 \times {@R_val@} \times {@C_val@}} = {@ta_alpha@}\;\text{rad/s}\]</p>
<p>\[\omega_0 = \frac{1}{\sqrt{LC}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{{@L_val@} \times {@C_val@}}} = {@ta_omega0@}\;\text{rad/s}\]</p>

<h4>Step 4: Damping Regime</h4>
<p>Comparing \(\alpha = {@ta_alpha@}\) with \(\omega_0 = {@ta_omega0@}\):</p>
<p>The circuit is <strong>{@regime_name@}</strong>.</p>

<h4>Step 5: General Form and Coefficients</h4>
<p>For a source-free (natural response) parallel RLC, the final value is zero.</p>
<p>General form: \(v_o(t) = {@ta6@}\)</p>

<p>Applying initial conditions:</p>
<ul>
  <li>\(v_o(0^+) = V_0 = {@V0_val@}\;\text{V}\)</li>
  <li>\(\frac{dv_o}{dt}(0^+) = -\frac{1}{C}\!\left(\frac{V_0}{R} + I_0\right) = {@dvdt0@}\;\text{V/s}\)</li>
</ul>
<p>Solving the system of two equations yields the complete response:</p>
<p>\[v_o(t) = {@ta_vo@}\;\text{V}, \quad t \geq 0\]</p>

<h4>Step 6: Final Value</h4>
<p>As \(t \to \infty\), all exponential terms decay to zero.
Since there is no source in the circuit for \(t > 0\), the final value is:</p>
<p>\[\lim_{t \to \infty} v_o(t) = 0\;\text{V}\]</p>

<hr />

<h4>Answer Summary</h4>
<table border="1" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0">
  <tr><th>Part</th><th>Quantity</th><th>Correct Answer</th></tr>
  <tr><td>(a)</td><td>\(V_0\)</td><td>{@ta1@} V</td></tr>
  <tr><td>(b)</td><td>\(I_0\)</td><td>{@ta2@} A</td></tr>
  <tr><td>(c)</td><td>\(\alpha\)</td><td>{@ta3@} rad/s</td></tr>
  <tr><td>(d)</td><td>\(\omega_0\)</td><td>{@ta4@} rad/s</td></tr>
  <tr><td>(e)</td><td>Damping regime</td><td>{@regime_name@}</td></tr>
  <tr><td>(f)</td><td>General form</td><td>\({@ta6@}\)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>(g)</td><td>\(v_o(t)\)</td><td>\({@ta_vo@}\) V</td></tr>
  <tr><td>(h)</td><td>Final value</td><td>{@ta8@} V</td></tr>
</table>
]]></text>
  </generalfeedback>

